A Universal Structural Index: Arithmetic Recovery of
Recurrence in Text and Music
Emergent Identity, Meter and Rhythm from a Bijective
Arithmetic Braiding
Phillip Somerville (@unitambo)
April 2026
unitambo.wordpress.com
The Question
Can a zero-parameter arithmetic iterator — designed for lossless information encoding —
recover the structural recurrences of great literature and music without being told what
structure is?
The corpus assembled here is deliberately symmetric: four authors, four works — two
poems, two musical. Lewis Carroll’s Jabberwocky, John Keats’ Ode to Autumn, Claude
Debussy’s Clair de Lune, Johann Sebastian Bach’s Cello Suite No. 1 in G major. Three
centuries. Two art forms. One iterator. One precision floor. No rules. No training.
The answer, it turns out, is yes. And the results are surprising enough to warrant careful
examination.
The Construction
The quadratic iterator processes any payload as a sequential bit stream:
H[n] = TRUNC(ROUND((H[n-1]² − F[n])² − F[n], 14), 14)
F[n] ∈ {1.094, 1.096} — the payload bit at step n
Every payload has a canonical fixed-point digest D* satisfying run_iterator(P, D*) = D*. This
digest is seed-independent — it converges from any valid starting point within two loop
iterations. It is self-certifying and losslessly invertible given the ternary control stream B[].
The digest D* is a content-addressed scalar: identical for structurally equivalent payloads,
metrically close for structurally related ones. Formally, |D*(P₁) − D*(P₂)| satisfies identity,
symmetry, and the triangle inequality — a proven metric over the space of payload strings.
The dynamics are those of a dissipative ping-pong oscillator. The iterator bounces between
two attractor basins — H≈0.086 and H≈0.089 — driven by the payload’s bit stream. Long
runs of identical bits produce extended dwell phases. Rapid alternation produces burst
clusters of ternary events. The Lyapunov spectrum is entirely negative (mean λ≈−0.969):
purely contractive, no chaos. This places the construction at the opposite pole from neural
networks at the edge of stability — where Tuci et al. (arXiv:2604.19740) show that fractal
attractors assist generalisation. Here, lossless encoding is achieved by eliminating chaos
entirely.
The ternary control stream B[] is a faithful step-by-step record of every basin crossing —
the full mixing history of the trajectory, preserved at unit resolution. The digest is where you
ended up. The control stream is everything that happened on the way.
The structure is made manifest.
The Corpus
Carroll: Jabberwocky
Carroll’s nonsense verse is the construction’s first test. Jabberwocky clusters 42.9% of its
lines into exact D* equivalence classes — the repeated opening stanza (four lines, appearing
identically at the poem’s close) collapses to identical digests. The rhyme scheme surfaces
naturally. The nonsense vocabulary — “brillig”, “mimsy”, “borogoves” — pulls a quarter of the
lines toward the low attractor basin, distinguishable from the majority. The iterator places
Carroll’s invented words in a different arithmetic neighbourhood from “the” and “and”
without being told they are unusual.
The strange loop at the heart of the corpus: “This loop is a strange loop” — processed by
the quadratic iterator — converges to a fixed point in exactly 2 loops, self-certifying its own
recurrence. The string enacts what it names. Hofstadter would recognise this.
Type-token ratio: 0.545. Hapax rate: 61.5%. Carroll repeats heavily — and the index shows
it.
Keats: Ode to Autumn
Keats clusters only 6.7% of lines. Every line is essentially unique. The type-token ratio
(0.693) and hapax rate (85.1%) confirm independently what the index shows arithmetically:
Keats almost never repeats. Three quarters of his vocabulary appears exactly once.
The most striking Keats result is not the clustering but its absence in the D* standard
deviation. Despite longer lines and richer vocabulary, Keats’ lines cluster more tightly in D*
space than Carroll’s (std 1.17e-04 vs 1.68e-04). The iambic pentameter metre imposes a
consistent rhythmic structure that the iterator detects as geometric proximity — all lines
driven by the same stress pattern arrive in the same attractor neighbourhood. The metre is
visible as D* clustering even when the words are not.
83% of Keats lines fall in the high attractor basin — the most consistently single-basin of
any text work in the corpus. The metrical regularity is doing this.
Keats’ rhyme scheme is partially recovered. The /iːz/ family (trees/bees/cease) collapses to
an exact D* equivalence class. The B rhymes (sun/run) are near-exact at 3e-14 distance.
The ABAB structure of the first stanza emerges from the arithmetic without instruction.
Debussy: Clair de Lune
The musical encoding uses full note names with standard flat notation (Ab, Eb, Gb, Db, Bb)
concatenated phrase by phrase — unambiguous and consistent. Microtonal inflection,
dynamics, and timing are discarded. What survives is unambiguous pitch sequence as a
character string. The same iterator that processed Carroll and Keats processes Debussy.
The results are not trivial.
The recapitulation. Debussy’s opening phrase — “AbAbAbFEbDb” — appears at P01, P03,
P15, P16, and P17 in the index. P15 and P16 are the structural recapitulation: the formal
return of the opening material after the climax. Their D* values are identical to P01 and P02
to 14 decimal places. The arithmetic detected the recapitulation without being told it exists.
The motivic equivalences. The post-climax descent (P13, P14) shares D* with the opening
theme — different note sequences arriving at the same harmonic destination. The rising
sequence and its descending answer collapse to a single equivalence class — opposite
directions of the same motivic cell, arithmetically equivalent. Clair de Lune clusters 66.7% of
phrases with the corrected encoding — the richest clustering in the literary corpus.
The energy contour. The J-stream ratio (J≠0 : J=0 events) tracks musical tension directly:
Melodic phrases (P01-P17): ratio 1.5 - 3.4 — active/arpeggio
Coda figures (P18-P20): ratio 1.2 - 1.4 — mixed/settling
Final note (P21): ratio 1.0 — stasis
As Debussy dissolves the texture in the coda, the J-stream ratio drops toward unity. The
oscillator feels the diminuendo. The arithmetic tracks the musical energy without hearing a
sound.
The climax. P12 — the rising line to the climax — has the highest overhead (0.793×) of any
phrase in the piece. Maximum musical tension = maximum arithmetic information density.
The iterator assigns the highest entropy score to the emotional high point.
Bach: Cello Suite No. 1 in G major
Bach is the ultimate test. His music is built on motivic economy — the systematic
development of small cells across an entire work. The Suite’s six movements — Prélude,
Allemande, Courante, Sarabande, Menuets I & II, Gigue — were encoded using full note
names with sharp notation (Fs for F#) in G major.
Bach clusters 56.5% of phrases into exact D* equivalence classes — eleven distinct
equivalence classes across six movements. The Allemande’s opening phrase recurs in
Menuet I. The descending scale of the Allemande shares D* with the Menuet I descent. The
D pedal figure spans three movements — Allemande, Menuet I, and Menuet II in G minor.
The closing phrase of the Allemande reappears in the Courante. The C major run is shared
between Courante and Gigue. The D pedal point recurs between Courante and Gigue.
Bach’s motivic economy — his habit of deriving multiple movements from the same cellular
material — is visible as arithmetic equivalence. The iterator quantifies what musicologists
describe qualitatively.
The Sarabande. The slowest movement has a D* std deviation of 3.26e-08 — near-zero, an
order of magnitude tighter than any other movement. All six Sarabande phrases cluster into
a single arithmetic neighbourhood. The stately, note-by-note character produces extended
dwell phases in both attractor basins. The music’s stillness is arithmetically visible.
The J-stream paradox. The Sarabande — the slowest movement — has the highest J-
stream ratio (1.747). The Courante — one of the fastest — has the lowest (1.393). Each
silence in the Sarabande creates a basin crossing when the next note arrives. The Gigue’s
rapid repeated arpeggios produce regular dwell phases within each figure. Speed
paradoxically creates regularity. Stillness creates activity. The iterator hears the difference.
