The portrait separates cleanly along two axes.
Clustering ranks the works by their internal repetition structure: Clair de Lune (66.7%) >
Bach (56.5%) > Jabberwocky (42.9%) > Keats (6.7%). Musical formal structure produces
the highest clustering. Romantic poetry the lowest.
D std deviation* ranks the works by their attractor tightness: Clair de Lune (1.49e-05) <
Keats (1.17e-04) < Bach (1.32e-04) < Carroll (1.68e-04). Debussy’s tonal consistency
produces the tightest clustering. Carroll’s varied rhyme scheme the widest spread.
The two axes are independent. Jabberwocky clusters heavily but spreads widely —
repetitive but phonologically varied. Keats clusters rarely but spreads narrowly — unique but
metrically consistent. The construction captures both dimensions simultaneously from the
same arithmetic.
What Is Being Recovered
These are not surface similarities. The construction performs no string matching, no
frequency counting, no edit distance calculation. It applies no music-theoretic rules, no
phonological alphabet, no trained similarity model.
What it recovers is arithmetic equivalence under the iterator’s dynamics. Two payloads
share a D* value when their bit sequences drive the same contractive attractor to the same
terminal state — when they are geometrically equivalent in the iterator’s phase space.
That equivalence corresponds to:
Exact repetition: Carroll’s repeated stanza, Debussy’s recapitulation, Bach’s returning
motifs — same bits, same digest
Motivic equivalence: Debussy’s descending answer sharing D* with the rising
sequence — opposite motion, same arithmetic destination
Cross-movement unity: Bach’s Allemande material recurring in Menuet I — the suite’s
internal architecture made visible
Metrical regularity: Keats’ iambic lines clustering in D* space — same rhythmic
geometry
Rhyme families: Carroll’s and Keats’ end-rhymes collapsing to equivalence classes —
shared suffix bit patterns
The structure is made manifest.
The Hofstadter Resonance
Hofstadter chose Bach, Escher, and Gödel for his exploration of self-reference and strange
loops. Bach’s fugues are the musical paradigm of self-referential structure — the subject
transforming itself through inversion, retrograde, augmentation. The Cello Suite No. 1
exhibits the same motivic economy across six movements. The iterator finds it.
The quadratic iterator is itself a strange loop: a construction designed to encode
information discovers, in the process of encoding, the structural identity of what it is
encoding. It was not designed to hear the recapitulation. It was not designed to feel the
diminuendo. It was not designed to find Bach’s cross-movement motivic unity. It was not
designed to detect the rhyme.
It found these things because they were always there — in the arithmetic geometry of the bit
stream, waiting for a contractive map at the right precision floor to make them visible.
The residual is not error. It is the signal. And tonight it played Clair de Lune and the Cello
Suite.
Honest Scope
The musical encoding uses full note names — unambiguous across all phrases. The
encoding is still reduced: microtonal inflection, dynamics, equal temperament relationships,
and timing are not present. The phrase boundaries are manually defined. A production
system would require automated segmentation and a richer encoding, potentially full MIDI
byte sequences.
Null model validation. Clustering rates were validated against 500 random string trials
matching each corpus in phrase count, length distribution, and character set. All four works
exceed the null distribution at Z > 15 (p << 0.001). Random strings of equivalent structure
cluster at 0–3.4%. The real works cluster at 6.7–66.7%. The structural signal is not noise.
Sarabande qualification. The Sarabande’s near-zero D* std deviation (3.26e-08) is
enhanced by space characters encoding rests — the spaces contribute to arithmetic
convergence. Without spaces the std deviation rises to 1.93e-04 (normal range). The
structural repeat P25==P29 is confirmed in both encodings. The clustering is real; the near-
zero std deviation is partially a spacing effect.
Key signature test. Harmonically unrelated phrases in G major show D* distances of 1e-4
to 3e-4 — they do not cluster together. The metric detects motivic structure, not key
signature alone.
Node-edge traversal. The digest chain was verified: all nodes independently confirmed, all
edges intact (digest[n] == seed[n+1] to 14dp), all entries self-certifying via fixed-point loop.
The index is reproducibly traversable. Full verification code is available at
unitambo.wordpress.com.
Bijectivity. Formal proof of bijectivity at fixed iterative depth remains an open question —
identified as the foundational next step in the main paper. The empirical results — zero
collisions across all tested payloads, exact structural detections, reproducible node-edge
traversal — are consistent with bijectivity but do not constitute proof. This is stated honestly
and the construction’s claims do not require the formal proof to stand.
Open Questions
Can the construction detect key signature as an attractor region? Does G major cluster
differently from D-flat major across multiple works?
Does the four-channel quad comparator (forward/reverse/complement/reverse complement)
detect musical inversion and retrograde — the compositional techniques Bach used
systematically in his fugues?
Can the J-stream KL divergence distinguish musical styles — Baroque counterpoint from
Impressionist harmony — as it distinguishes Carroll from Keats?
Does the fixed-point loop convergence rate vary with musical complexity — does a Bach
fugue converge differently from a Debussy nocturne?
These questions are tractable with the existing construction. No new machinery required.
